# construt a corpus
sample_crop <- corpus(sample_read)

# Summarize
summ = as.data.frame(summary(sample_crop))

summ$Size <- c(format(object.size(sample_read[1,2]), "GB", digits = 4), 
             format(object.size(sample_read[2,2]), "GB", digits = 4),
             format(object.size(sample_read[3,2]), "GB", digits = 4))

x1 <- summ$Size[1]
x1 <- as.numeric(stringr::word(x1, 1, 1))

x2 <- summ$Size[2]
x2 <- as.numeric(stringr::word(x2, 1, 1))

x3 <- summ$Size[3]
x3 <- as.numeric(stringr::word(x3, 1, 1))

summ$TTR <- round(c(summ$Types/summ$Tokens), 3)


totaltable = data.frame(Text = "Total",
                 Types = sum(summ$Types),
                 Tokens = sum(summ$Tokens),
                 Sentences = sum(summ$Sentences),
                 Size = paste(sum(x1,x2,x3), "Gb", sep = " "),
                 TTR = sum(round(c(summ$Types/summ$Tokens), 3))) 

summ = rbind(summ[,c(1,2,3,4,7,8)],totaltable)

How many unique words do you need in a frequency sorted dictionary to cover 50%

We need 109 unique words to cover 50% of all word instances in the language and 3461 unique words to cover 90%.

dfm_token_all <- dfm(sample_tokens, stem = TRUE)

# get frequency of each words
fre = textstat_frequency(dfm_token_all)

# total number of words
totalfreq = sum(fre$frequency) # 698547

sumCover = 0
maxlimt = length(fre$frequency)  # number of unique words 34013

for(i in 1: maxlimt) {
  sumCover <- sumCover + fre$frequency[i]
  if(sumCover >= 0.5*totalfreq){break}
}
print(i) # 109
## [1] 109
sumCover = 0
maxlimt = length(fre$frequency)
for(i in 1: maxlimt) {
  sumCover <- sumCover + fre$frequency[i]
  if(sumCover >= 0.9*totalfreq){break}
}
print(i) # 3461
## [1] 3461

How do you evaluate how many of the words come from foreign languages?

The Unicode Standard is the universal character encoding standard used for representation of text for computer processing. UTF-8 (8-bit Unicode Transformation Format) is a variable-width character encoding capable of encoding all 1,112,064 valid characters. Unicode Supported scripts include not only pan-European scripts and Asian scripts but also complex text layout scripts such as Arabic, Hebrew, Hindi, and Thai. We could identify foreign language using code table available online. Chick [here] http://www.unicode.org/standard/supported.html for more detals.
